@NODE INTRODUCTION "What this program does"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
This  program is used to convert an IFF animation into a SFMV animation.  It
also  allows you to alter the settings of a previously created SFMV file.  A
simple  Graphical  User  Interface has been used to allow easy access to all
the SFMV options.

For   more   information   about   the  SFMV  file  format  please  see  the
@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN} file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADIFF "Loading an IFF animation"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
To  load  an  IFF  animation,  simply  click  on the @{FG SHINE}'Load IFF Anim'@{FG TEXT} option.
You'll  then be presented with a standard system file requester, select your
file and it will be loaded in.

The  IFF  Animation that you choose to convert must be 16 colours and have a
screen size of 160 x 128 or 160 x 100.  If the animation size is larger than
this then it will be truncated when converted.  An animation that is smaller
than the above sizes will not be accepted.

The  number  of  frames  in  the animation are limited only by the amount of
memory you have available.

@ENDNODE
@NODE SFMVIO "Loading and Saving SFMV animations"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
A  SFMV  animation can be loaded by clicking on @{FG SHINE}'Load SFMV Anim'@{FG TEXT}.  This will
then  allow  you  to  alter the flag settings of the SFMV file, you can then
re-save the file with the @{FG SHINE}'Save SFMV Anim'@{FG TEXT} button.

The  @{FG SHINE}'Save  SFMV Anim'@{FG TEXT} button is also used to save out an animation that has
been converted from an original IFF animation file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE IFFPLAY "Playing IFF animations"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The @{FG SHINE}'Playback IFF'@{FG TEXT} button allows you to view the IFF animation that you have
previously  loaded.   This  option  is  for  checking  the  animation before
conversion.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SFMVCONV "Converting IFF animations to SFMV format"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The  @{FG SHINE}'Convert  To  SFMV'@{FG TEXT}  button  is  probably the most important button, it
initiates  the conversion process.  It will go through each frame of the IFF
animation  and  convert it into the SFMV format.  While the conversion is in
progress  either  the  progress window or the animation frames will be shown
(depending  on  the @{"TOOLTYPES" LINK TOOLTYPES settings).  The 'Amiga-M' keyboard combination
can  be  used  to  flip  between  the  workbench and animation screen.  Once
converted the SFMV animation can be saved with the @{FG SHINE}'Save SFMV Anim'@{FG TEXT} button.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONVBUF "Conversion Buffer size"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The  size  of  the  conversion  buffer  can  be changed with the buffer size
gadget.   All  animations will fit into a @{FG SHINE}'Half RAW'@{FG TEXT} buffer, however you may
not  have enough memory to use a buffer of this size (especially if your IFF
animation  is  large).   A  @{FG SHINE}'Quarter RAW'@{FG TEXT} buffer is half the size again, and
finally  @{FG SHINE}'1.5  x  IFF'@{FG TEXT} is the smallest buffer.  This buffer size is probably
the best to use for most animations, the SFMV compaction routines are fairly
close to IFF compaction methods.
	Most  SFMV  animations  should compact to around the same size as an
IFF  file.  However if your animation contains many sequentially frames that
contain  an  almost  identical  image,  then the resulting SFMV file will be
quite  a bit larger.  This is due to the compaction methods used, however we
are  currently  developing  methods to allow SFMV animations to be compacted
better and to also allow individual frames to have timing information.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DISPLAY "The Convertor window"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The SFMV Convertor display is, hopefully, self-explanatory.  However a brief
discription of the window display follows...

The window itself is divided into six areas.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'IFF Anim Information' and 'SFMV Information'@{FG TEXT}
These  panels  contain  information regarding the animation formats that are
loaded into the program.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'SFMV Options'@{FG TEXT}
This  panel contains the flag settings for SFMV files, these options control
the way that the file is played back by the player.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Compaction'@{FG TEXT}
This  panel  has  information  regarding how well the IFF animation has been
compressed.

@{FG FILL}'Raw  %'@{FG TEXT} refers to the size of the SFMV animation compared to raw data
needed for the animation.

@{FG FILL}'IFF %'@{FG TEXT} is the size compared to the orignal IFF size.

@{FG FILL}'Buf %'@{FG TEXT} is the amount of the compaction buffer that has currently been used.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Button area@{FG TEXT}
This area contains the gadgets for using the convertor.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Status'@{FG TEXT}
This  panel  gives  information  to  the  user,  such  as error messages and
warnings.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOOPING "SFMV animation looping"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The  SFMV  format  allows  the  animation to be looped a specified amount of
times,  setting  the @{FG SHINE}'Looped?'@{FG TEXT} checkbox enables looping and the @{FG SHINE}'Loop Count'@{FG TEXT}
number  gadget  specifies the number of times to loop, a value of zero means
that the loop will be infinite.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FADING "SFMV animation fading"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Convertor@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The  SFMV  format  allows for the animation to be faded in and out.  Setting
the  @{FG SHINE}'Fade In?'@{FG TEXT} option will cause the player to fade the animation up before
playback.   The  @{FG SHINE}'Fade  Out?'@{FG TEXT}  option  will  cause  the  player  to fade the
animation down after playback.
@ENDNODE
